Pour the @couscous{100%g} and half the @stock{1%sachet} into a #bowl{}.

Stir in 200ml boiling @water{200%ml} (500ml for 4p).

Cover with a #plate{} or #cling film{}.

Leave aside for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Place a #large pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, add the pepper and @Irish pork mince{250%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. Pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Use a #spoon{} to break up the mince as it cooks. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Add the @ras-el-hanout{2%sachet} and fry for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, remaining @stock{1%sachet} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} (double for 4p).

Cover and simmer for ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once simmered, stir through the @peas{120%g} and a knob of @butter{to taste}.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} to loosen the sauce if you feel it's too thick. Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and divide between #bowls{}.

Serve topped with ras-el-hanout spiced pork.

Drizzle over the @cranberry chutney{1%sachet}.

Finish with a dollop of @yoghurt{75%g}.